sentences: Ivana Fišer (born Fischer; June 13, 1905 – September 7, 1967) was known Croatian Jewish conductor.
Fišer was born in Zagreb on June 13, 1905 to a Jewish family of well-known Croatian architect Ignjat Fischer and his wife Helena (née Egersrodfer).
From 1931 to 1934, Fišer worked as violinist at the Croatian Music Institute orchestra.
As a conductor, Fišer debuted in 1933 while directing the comic opera Bastien und Bastienne with Zagreb philharmonic orchestra.
From 1939 to 1941, she led the Zagreb Red Cross orchestra.
Until 1941, she also led the Osijek philharmonic orchestra.
From 1947 to 1965, Fišer worked as a prompter at the Croatian National Theatre in Zagreb.
